    "articles": {
        "lemonde": [
            "LIVE, war in the Middle East: more than 210 dead in Lebanon; Donald Trump not hostile to a cleric at the head of Iran. \nAround 300,000 people have been displaced in Lebanon, according to the NGO Norwegian Refugee Council, due to Israeli bombing targeting the southern suburbs of Beirut and southern Lebanon. For his part, the American president demanded “unconditional surrender” from Iran.\n\nIn the Strait of Hormuz, the story of sailors stranded and in danger. \nVIDEO In the Strait of Hormuz, visual stories of sailors stranded and in danger\n\nTrial of Tariq Ramadan for rape: an arrest warrant issued by France. \nThe preacher is in Switzerland and has still not appeared for his trial which opened on Monday. Two doctors have ruled that he is fit to stand trial.\n\nLIVE, war in Ukraine: after a skirmish between Ukraine and Hungary, the EU deplores “unacceptable” threats from Volodymyr Zelensky against Viktor Orban. \n“We hope that one person in the EU will not block the 90 billion. Otherwise, we will give the address of this person to our armed forces,” the Ukrainian president said, referring to the Hungarian prime minister who is blocking the 90 billion euro loan that Brussels wants to pay to Kiev.\n\nChina's very cautious new climate ambitions are distancing it from its international commitments. \nDespite the massive deployment of renewable energy, China's new five-year plan sets a target of 17% reduction in carbon intensity, insufficient to meet the commitments made by the country in the Paris agreement.\n\nHélène Mouchard-Zay, tireless fighter for the memory of the victims of the Vichy regime, is dead. \nDaughter of Jean Zay, Minister of the Popular Front assassinated by the Militia in 1944, she worked to have her ashes transferred to the Pantheon in 2015. She died on March 2 at the age of 85.\n\nWith the album “Kiss All the Time. Disco, Occasionally,” Harry Styles is putting his pop star title back on the line. \nHighly anticipated, since the triumph of “Harry’s House” (2022), the Englishman’s fourth solo record takes an electronic route, with more or less success.",
            "“Profit close to zero”: fatigue of empty speeches for employees trained in management. \nEvery year, thousands of executives are trained in leadership and management by their companies. But, for some, the account is not there: these few days are not enough to deal with the problems encountered on a daily basis.\n\nIn Formula 1, the cards are being reshuffled after the major upheaval of the new regulations. \nDriving completely renewed single-seaters, due to a change in rules, F1 drivers launch the 2026 season on Sunday at the Australian Grand Prix. Despite the uncertainties, McLaren aspires to retain its titles against Mercedes, Red Bull and Ferrari.\n\nMunicipal elections in Montauban: seven contenders to win the chair of Brigitte Barèges. \nAfter twenty-three years at the head of the city, the former mayor, who moved to the extreme right, left the local political scene, struck by ineligibility. Between the war of succession and the major issues at stake, the future scenario is struggling to become clearer.\n\nIn “Celeste”, on Arte.tv, the actress Carmen Machi, revealed by “La Mesias”, is astonishing as Tax Columbo. \nThe Spanish actress takes on the role of an inspector responsible for bringing down an international pop star, Celeste, played by Andrea Bayardo.\n\nThe ultra-trail, a field of study for science. \n“Ten thousand steps and counting.” French and American researchers conducted in-depth tests on twenty-three trail runners. Verdict: if long-distance running accelerates the aging of red blood cells, scientists want to be reassuring.\n\n“We also see sex scenes filmed”: when Meta glasses subcontractors in Nairobi see everything, really everything. \nTwo Swedish media outlets have revealed that employees of a Meta subcontractor in Kenya are viewing images captured by “Ray-Ban Meta” smart glasses, including intimate scenes. A complaint was filed in the United States.",
            "Album selection: Alexander Malofeev, Christelle Séry and Etienne Cabaret, Joshua Idehen, Michel Houellebecq and Frédéric Lo, Baby Keem, Lucas Santtana. \nTo listen this week: the Russian pianist's first double album revealed in 2014 by the Tchaikovsky Young Musicians Competition; two masters in the art of “free” sound; 16 new tracks from the British singer and poet of Nigerian origin; a collaboration around poetry between the writer and the musician; the second opus of the American rapper, cousin of Kendrick Lamar; the 11 new songs in 8 languages ​​from the Bahian musician.\n\nThe death of the “Dawson” actor or the end of a fantasy America. \n“Total Screen.” The premature death of James Van Der Beek, famous for the role of Dawson in the series of the same name, follows those of several actors who left their mark on television in the 1990s. With them, an entire era disappears. And the image of a certain America.\n\nWith tens of thousands of jobs destroyed, the health of the American economy is worrying. \nThe world's largest economy destroyed 92,000 jobs in February, and unemployment rose slightly to 4.4%, according to official data released Friday.\n\n2026 Paralympic Games: “Make the Milan-Cortina Games a springboard for the success of the 2030 French Alps”. \nAndrew Parsons, president of the International Paralympic Committee, and Marie-Amélie Le Fur, patron of the French Paralympic and Sports Committee, discuss for “Le Monde” the importance of the Milan-Cortina Winter Paralympic Games which begin on Friday and will run until March 15."
        ],
        "mediapart": [
            "“Mamadou”, “Bordeaux or Yemen?”: the RN candidate in Pau tries to forget her racist posts. \nThe head of the far-right party list in Pau, Margaux Taillefer, has deleted several racist, LGBTphobic and fatphobic publications posted in recent years on the social network X. This former Zemmourist is now seeking to smooth out her image.\n\nMunicipal: the trial by fire for Politicae, the school of mayors financed by Pierre-Édouard Stérin. \nThe training institute supported by the ultraconservative billionaire hopes to see its students win thousands of town halls in municipal elections. Several candidates supported by Politicae, however, are distancing themselves from the reactionary agenda of Pierre-Édouard Stérin.\n\nLebanon and Iran under bombs, Trump demands “unconditional surrender” from Iran. \nDonald Trump demanded the “unconditional surrender” of Iran after a week of war, explosions once again shaking Tehran and Lebanon on Friday, causing a mass exodus of residents of the southern suburbs of Beirut.\n\nZiad Majed on Lebanon: “Israel is in a logic of total war”. \nAs Hezbollah supports Iran, Israel “took the opportunity to widen the conflict” and is now threatening to strike Beirut. Researcher and political scientist Ziad Majed discusses the new issues emerging in Lebanon.\n\n“Public media are under attack almost everywhere in Europe.” \nPublic broadcasting is facing a drastic drop in its resources, when it is not threatened with political takeover. For Christina Holtz-Bacha, professor emeritus in communication sciences, it is urgent to reaffirm its missions of general interest.\n\nIn Switzerland, public broadcasting endangered by a vote. \nSwiss voters must decide whether they want to reduce the license fee and cut almost half of the public broadcasting budget. A new episode of the culture war which endangers the diversity of Switzerland.\n\nEpstein files: Justice Department releases testimony accusing Donald Trump. \nNew documents were made public Thursday March 5. Three are particularly explosive because they directly implicate the Republican president. A woman accuses him of raping her in the 1980s, when she was a minor.",
            "Despair grips the displaced people of Beirut, left to their own devices. \nThe day after an Israeli order for a mass evacuation of the southern suburbs of the Lebanese capital, families taking refuge in the city center fear a long war and “indiscriminate strikes”. “The United States and Israel are lost, and they are losing us with them,” says a resident.\n\nDisability: La Poste sentenced to 100,000 euros for discrimination against an employee. \nAfter more than five years of being put on the shelf, a former postwoman, recognized as a disabled worker, had La Poste condemned and her dismissal canceled. But his reinstatement, pronounced in June, is still not effective.\n\nBaden-Württemberg: the “made in Germany” crisis is making its way to the polls. \nThe rich South-West land is hit by the crisis of an automobile sector which has missed the electric shift. Without appropriate policies, the risk is that of a lasting decline and a rise of the extreme right. The results of the regional election on March 8 will be closely scrutinized."
        ]
    },
